<FIRST>u a AM-TankerSpill 3rdLd-Writethru a0593 04-02 1276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0593,1309</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shifting Oil Causing Headaches; Skipped Charged</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 1st to UPDATE with newspaper report of
captain admitting drinking before and after boarding vessel, picks up 3rd
graf pvs, `The bulk...'; INSERTS 6 grafs after 12th pvs, `Police in ...'
to ADD background from prosecutor, picks up 13th graf pvs, `FBI officials
...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserColor VDX5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities issued an arrest warrant for
the tanker captain suspected of drinking before his ship ran
aground, causing a 1,000-square-mile oil slick that expanded
Saturday under shifting wind and currents.
   A prosecutor said the captain admitted drinking on board the
tanker before it went aground, according to court papers obtained
by The Oregonian of Portland newspaper.
   One of the first investigators to board the Exxon Valdez asked
Joseph Hazelwood what the problem was, and the captain replied, ``I
think you're looking at it,'' the newspaper reported in its Sunday
editions.
   Meanwhile, Alaska's governor threatened to close the
Trans-Alaska Pipeline if the oil industry fails to protect against
future spills.
   The bulk of the 10.1-million-gallon slick began moving toward
Cordova about 50 miles southeast of here, threatening the home
waters of fishermen who have struggled to save endangered fish
hatcheries.
   About 800 miles of beach have been tainted so far in the biggest
oil spill in the nation's history, officials said.
   Gov. Steve Cowper said the state will require ``absolute proof
that equipment is in place'' to combat future oil spills. ``If it's
not done, we're authorized to close the pipeline,'' he said.
   Some 85 percent of the state's $2 billion budget comes from the
pipeline, and although the state has a $10 billion savings account,
oil production on Alaska's North slope accounts for 25 percent of
U.S. production.
   Alaska Attorney General Doug Baily said Saturday that criminal
charges were filed late Friday against Hazelwood, 42, captain of
the tanker that crashed into Bligh Reef in Prince William Sound on
March 24.
   Exxon fired Hazelwood on Thursday, the same day the National
Transportation Safety Board revealed blood and urine tests taken
about nine hours after the accident showed he had been under the
influence of alcohol.
   Charges filed in Valdez District Court accuse Hazelwood of
operating a motorcraft while under the influence of alcohol,
reckless endangerment and the negligent discharge of oil, all
misdemeanors.
   The three offenses carry combined maximum sentences of two years
and three months in prison, and fines totaling up to $10,000.
District Attorney Larry Weeks said if convicted, Hazelwood would
have to spend at least 30 days in jail because he has two prior
drunken driving convictions in the past five years.
   Valdez Magistrate Tracee Schnell signed the arrest warrant for
Hazelwood, and set bond at $50,000. Authorities believe he left the
state several days ago, but Baily said the state would seek his
extradition.
   Police in Hazelwood's hometown of Huntington, N.Y., said
Saturday they did not know his whereabouts.
   The Oregonian said two crewmen told authorities they saw
Hazelwood drinking in Valdez before the ship left port.
   A statement filed by Leonard M. Linton, an assistant district
attorney in Valdez, said one crewman saw Hazelwood consume four
alcoholic drinks while still in port.
   Linton's affidavit said two other unidentified witnesses said
they smelled alcohol on Hazelwood's breath when the captain was on
the bridge, the newspaper reported.
   ``One witness said that Hazelwood appeared to be under the
influence of intoxicating beverages and that his balance was not
good,'' Linton said in the affidavit.
   However, all crewmen interviewed by Alaska state troopers have
said Hazelwood ``did not appear to be intoxicated,'' Linton wrote.
   Hazelwood apparently told investigators he drank one beer before
leaving port and a couple of bottles of ``moussy,'' a beverage
containing 0.5 percent alcohol, after he returned to the ship,
Linton said.
   FBI officials in Washington say they're investigating possible
felony violations of the Clean Water Act, which prohibits the
``negligent discharge of a pollutant into navigable waters.''
   Exxon is liable for millions of dollars in fines under state law
if it is proven to be negligent in causing the spill and cleaning
it up.
   Shifting wind drove the main body of the slick east toward
Hinchenbrook Island, which forms the primary boundary between the
sound and the Gulf of Alaska.
   The movement of the oil toward the rich fishing grounds at the
mouth of the Copper River stirred fear in Cordova, which lies on
the east side of the sound. Some Cordova fishermen, who had mounted
a bold effort to protect the hatcheries on the west side, headed
back toward their home port to battle the oil there.
   Larry Dietrick of the Alaska Department of Environmental
Conservation praised the Cordova fishermen as the ``backbone'' of
the cleanup and containment effort so far.
   Leaders in the fishing and tourist town of Seward, the first
community downstream from Prince William Sound to the west, also
went on the offensive, deploying 10,000 feet of boom the town
ordered from a Massachusetts manufacturer to protect salmon river
habitats.
   ``We're not going to let it happen,'' said Harry Gieseler, mayor
of the town 125 miles southwest of Valdez. ``We're taking our own
initiative.''
   At the Kenai Fjords National Park, near Seward, a team was sent
out to survey wildlife and evaluate the state of the park before
oil reaches the rocky shores, spokeswoman Dixie Dies said.
   The park will count on the city of Seward for boom and other
protective measures, she said.
   The Coast Guard rejected a plea from oil producers to ease
restrictions placed on tanker traffic into Valdez following the
spill. The Atlantic Richfield Co. said tanker movement from the
marine terminal of the trans-Alaska oil pipeline needs to be
stepped up to ensure adequate supplies on the West Coast.
   On Friday, wholesale gasoline prices surged as commodities
traders speculated that the squeeze in oil supplies caused by the
disastrous spill won't ease soon. Gas prices at the pump jumped by
as much as 10 cents a gallon in parts of California.
   Normally three to four loaded tankers leave Valdez daily. Since
the spill, only five have made it out. The Coast Guard has ordered
tugboat escorts until the tankers pass the grounded Exxon Valdez.
Local harbor pilots are required to accompany the tankers for
longer distances than usual.
   The Coast Guard said the restrictions would not be lifted until
the Exxon Valdez is refloated and moved to a safe anchorage,
possibly next week. Workers continued Saturday to pump oil from the
crippled tanker onto the Exxon San Francisco.
   Biologists walking beaches have counted 520 oiled birds
representing 20 species, fish and game officials said. Ten sea
otters and 27 oiled birds were taken to Valdez for cleaning, and
federal bird experts said more than 1,000 tainted birds _ some
alive, some dead _ had been spotted on a single island. They
expected the number to increase dramatically.
   Wildlife experts also were considering the possibility of
sending some sea otters to other states for care and
rehabilitation. Biologists say they expect to be inundated by
otters, the marine mammal most vulnerable to oil contamination
because of the loss of insulation and buoyancy of their fur.
   A sablefish harvest set to open today was canceled because of
the spill. Officials previously halted the shrimp harvest, which
was open for about two weeks before the spill and was to have run
until mid-April.
   Meanwhile, another in a series of class-action lawsuits was
filed Friday. A class-action complaint by San Francisco attorney
Melvin Belli, on behalf of area fishermen, asked for $2 billion,
half of it in punitive damages.
</TEXT>
