<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia 4thLd-Writethru a0580 04-02 0889</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0580,0915</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Africa Threatens To Remove U.N. Force After Guerrilla Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with revised casualty toll in
fighting; U.N. team sent to investigate; pickup graf 15 pvs `Fewer than...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa reported major clashes
with guerrillas hours before Namibia began its transition to
independence Saturday and said it may ask the U.N. force monitoring
the process to leave.
   Government-run radio said early Sunday that 36 guerrillas were
killed and two captured in fighting Friday night with South-West
African police, who suffered two deaths and nine injuries.
   The figures, attributed to a spokesman for territorial
Administrator-General Louis Pienaar, slightly revised those given
Saturday by South African officials.
   Foreign Minister Pik Botha of South Africa said Saturday that 38
guerrillas and two territorial policemen were killed when
guerrillas of the South-West African People's Organization, or
SWAPO, infiltrated from Angola on Friday evening.
   ``This is a most serious development,'' said Botha.
   The reported attack came hours before a formal cease-fire took
effect and a 20-nation U.N. peacekeeping force began overseeing the
end of South Africa's 74-year rule over Namibia.
   Police blocked thousands of SWAPO supporters who tried to march
in the capital to celebrate the transition.
   Botha accused the rebels of a flagrant violation of a pledge to
halt hostilities and said he had complained to U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   Unless there is a satisfactory response from the United Nations,
Botha said, South Africa would feel compelled to ask the
peacekeeping force to leave ``until SWAPO can be brought to its
senses.''
   In New York, U.N. spokeswoman Nadia Younes released a statement
from Perez de Cuellar saying: ``The secretary-general is greatly
concerned that such incidents have been reported. He has told Mr.
Botha that UNTAG (the U.N. Transition Assistance Group) is
immediately sending a team to investigate the reports.''
   U.N. Special Representative Martti Ahtisaari sent four senior
U.N. military, civilian, and police personnel to northern Namibia
to investigate the South African report. He was expected to make
his report by Sunday evening.
   An official of SWAPO, which has waged a war for independence
since 1966, said the organization would need a day or so to
determine what had happened but added that SWAPO ``has gone out of
its way to avoid conflict.''
   According to Botha, Perez de Cuellar indicated he might agree
that South Africa could reactivate its troops to guard against
SWAPO operations. But the U.N. spokeswoman said the
secretary-geeneral would have no comment on Botha's remarks.
   Later at a news conference, Botha said South African troops will
be allowed to leave their bases to search for the guerrillas
involved in the fighting if police can't control the situation.
   South African and SWAPO forces were confined to their bases as
of Saturday under the U.N. plan but Pienaar said SWAPO units had
not complied.
   Botha interrupted his airport news conference to take a call
from Pienaar. He then said that Pienaar, Ahtisaari and Gen. Prem
Chand, the UNTAG commander, said certain South African units would
be released from their bases to provide support to the police and
the U.N. group would monitor the South African movement.
   Fewer than 800 of the 4,500 military personnel assigned to the
UNTAG have arrived in Namibia.
   There had been no fighting since September between South African
and SWAPO forces, which were supposed to be restricted to their
bases as of midnight Friday under U.N. Resolution 435.
   The resolution establishes a process for elections in November
leading to independence early next year for Namibia, Africa's last
territory.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, completing an African
tour, flew into Windhoek to meet with Botha, U.N. officials and
British members of the U.N. monitoring force.
   Mrs. Thatcher said a special session of the U.N. Security
Council should be called to consider the alleged SWAPO incursion.
   ``This a most serious challenge to the authority of the United
Nations and the agreement, and we condemn it totally,'' she said.
   There was a tense 30-minute standoff outside the capital when
about 100 policemen confronted up to 20,000 SWAPO supporters
marching to Windhoek from the black township of Katatura, seeking
to celebrate the start of the independence process.
   Church leaders persuaded the marchers to return to Katatura,
where celebration rallies by rival political factions were held
during the day.
   About 400 SWAPO supporters reached downtown Windhoek and held a
rally across from a luxury hotel. About 30 policemen watched but
did not interfere as the crowd chanted, ``SWAPO, we win!''
   Until independence, administration of the territory and
responsibility for law enforcement will remain in the hands of
Pienaar, appointed by South Africa.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since it captured the territory
from the Germans in World War I.
   U.N. peacekeepers will monitor the election in November of a
constituent assembly. The assembly will later set up a black
majority government. Of Namibia's 1.3 million residents, about
70,000 are white.
   SWAPO is favored in the pre-independence elections, but whether
it can gain the two-thirds support needed to have complete control
over the drafting of a constitution is uncertain.
   The South Africans agreed to a U.N. independence plan for
Namibia in December as part of a southwestern Africa accord that
also calls for Cuban troops to be withdrawn from Angola.
</TEXT>
