<FIRST>u a AM-BridgeCollapse 2ndLd-Writethru a0713 04-02 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bridge Collapse, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0713,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bridge Collapse Leaves At Least Seven Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 1 graf to UPDATE with 7 bodies recovered; INSERTS
4 grafs after 8th graf, `We've got ..., to UPDATE with inspectors meeting
Monday, high water not considered cause. Pick up 9th graf, `The highway
...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MX1,2,3,4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COVINGTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers pulled seven bodies from a murky,
rain-swollen river Sunday where at least that many people died when
a 50-year-old U.S. highway bridge collapsed.
   The search for more victims continued but was hampered by bridge
debris and muddy waters, said state Highway Patrol Lt. Larry
Durham. The cause of the collapse was unknown.
   Searchers did not know how many victims might be in the river,
said Leroy Bledsoe, team director for nine divers working at the
site.
   Authorities said they had found a tractor-trailer rig and four
cars which plunged into the river when a large chunk of the
two-lane roadway fell 25 feet into the river about 8:45 p.m. CST
Saturday.
   They planned to continue to search ``until we're sure there are
no other vehicles or victims in there,'' Bledsoe said.
   The collapse left a 60-foot gap in the two-lane, northbound
bridge carrying U.S. Highway 51 over the Hatchie River five miles
north of here and about 45 miles north of Memphis. A companion,
two-lane bridge for southbound traffic was unaffected.
   Ron Collins of the Tennessee Emergency Management Agency said
bridge-building experts planned to study the bridge to try to find
out why it collapsed.
   ``We've got the state Department of Transportation here. Their
bridge survey team is going to survey the pilings of both bridges
and do some soundings and we'll just have to go from there,'' he
said.
   State bridge inspectors plan to meet Monday morning with the
National Transportation Safety Board, according to Covington Fire
Chief Jerry Craig.
   The river is slightly swollen from heavy rainfall last month,
Craig said.
   ``We've had an unusual amount of rainfall last month. The river
is out of its banks, and there's backwater all over the place. But
this happens twice a year, every year, and has for the past 100
years,'' Craig said.
   ``The river is actually just barely out of its banks. We don't
feel it had any bearing on the collapse,'' said Craig.
   The Highway Patrol closed the southbound roadway shortly after
the collapse and traffic was routed around the area.
   One victim was identified as Billy Herron Sr. of Ripley,
believed to be 49 or 50, said Donna Pugh, a spokeswoman for Baptist
Memorial Hospital Lauderdale in Ripley. The names of the other six
were withheld until relatives were notified.
   The bodies of three victims, a man, a woman and a child, were
recovered Saturday night. They apparently had been riding together
in one car, Collins said.
   The Hatchie, which runs generally east to west across the middle
of West Tennessee, was at 14.7 feet, 2.7 feet over flood stage,
about where the accident occurred, the National Weather Service
reported. It was not raining at the time of the collapse, but it
had been raining in previous days.
   Bledsoe said swift currents and the dark water were hindering
the search.
   ``It's pitch black in there,'' he said.
   Larry Prater of Covington said residents have been concerned for
some time that the bridge was getting old. Prater said three of his
relatives were in a pickup truck that drove over the bridge not
long before it collapsed.
   ``I was telling my wife the other day, saying `That bridge with
as much water as we've had is a dangerous thing,''' he said.
   Aging highway bridges have collapsed in other states in recent
years. In April 1987, an upstate New York span collapsed, killing
10 people. In 1983, part of the Mianus Bridge in Connecticut
collapsed, killing three people.

</TEXT>
