<HEAD>Floods in Eastern Australia Claim at Least Two Lives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Torrential rains along Australia's east
coast have caused flooding that that has claimed at least two
lives, police said Sunday.
   Two other people were missing and presumed drowned when a bridge
collapsed, the police said.
   Officials said a water department employee perished Saturday
when floodwaters overturned his boat in the Murrimbidgee River at
Casurina Sands, west of Canberra.
   A man died in Queensland state because of the flooding, police
said, but no details were available.
   Seven people were swept away when the rampaging Tweed River
collapsed a bridge at Murwillumbah in northern New South Wales
state. Police said five people were rescued early Sunday but two
are missing.
   Helicopters were sent to Murwillumbah to rescue victims of the
flooding that followed 48 hours of rain..
   One helicopter lifted 15 people from rooftops in the town and
navy helicopters rescued five schoolchildren stranded in the
Murwillumbah area, officials reported.
   Ted Pickering, the New South Wales minister of police and
emergency services, advised thousands of people living near the
Nepean, Hawkesbury and Georges rivers in the Sydney region to
prepare for possible evacuation.
   The Pacific Highway, the main road link between Sydney and
Brisbane, was flooded in several places.

