<HEAD>Thousands Participate In Abortion Rights March Through San Francisco</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 5th graf, `The march ..., to UPDATE with
New York demonstration. Pick up 6th graf, `Activists on ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 20,000 people marched through
downtown on Sunday in a noisy abortion rights demonstration that
organizers called the largest pro-choice gathering ever held in the
San Francisco Bay Area.
   Police estimated the crowd at about 20,000, but organizers of
the ``March for Women's Lives'' said more than 30,000 people
participated in the march and rally at City Hall.
   Margaret Connell, 59, of Santa Barbara, marched with her
85-year-old mother and 30-year-old daughter. They carried a sign
that said ``Three generations for choice.''
   ``I think what's before us is a choice of whether abortion is
safe and legal or whether abortion is unsafe and illegal,'' said
Connell. ``It's not whether there's going to be abortion.''
   The march, which was expected to attract supporters from as far
away as Oregon and Washington state, was held in conjunction with a
scheduled April 9 abortion rights rally in Washington, D.C.
   In New York City, about 400 abortion rights activists, some
hoisting giant clothes hangers, pushed against anti-abortionists in
a demonstration in front of St. Patrick's Cathedral.
   In a rare show of civil disobedience marking what a rally leader
called ``a turning point'' in the abortion rights movement, nine
activists were arrested for trespassing on church property and
disorderly conduct.
   ``Cardinal O'Connor, we know your position, you are the head of
the new Inquisition!'' shouted the protesters, who say that
Cardinal John O'Connor and the Roman Catholic hierarchy are
endorsing violence against women by supporting radical
anti-abortionists.
   Neither O'Connor nor his spokesman returned messages seeking
comment on the protest.
   Activists on both sides of the issue have been galvanized by a
recent U.S. Supreme Court decision to hear a case that could
overturn legal protections for abortion that were guaranteed by the
court's 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision.
   Many participants said that threat prompted them to gather in
the streets to publicly express their views.
   ``It's the timing with the court,'' said Ann Murphy, 43, of
Berkeley. ``Our position doesn't mean we're telling people to have
an abortion, because there's nothing worse than a child that's
unloved and unwanted. ... It's a matter of respecting opinions.''
   The rally also comes at a time when several anti-abortion
groups, including Operation Rescue, have held numerous protests at
clinics around the nation.
   In Miami, a suburban abortion clinic was blockaded for more than
an hour Saturday by anti-abortion demonstrators. Police arrested
137 people on trespassing charges.
   On Friday, 83 people were arrested for blocking access to an
abortion clinic in Boca Raton, Fla., and an arson fire early Friday
caused $65,000 damage to an abortion clinic in Ocala, Fla.
   Sunday's San Francisco march brought a sharp reaction from
anti-abortion activists.
   ``Although the marchers purport to represent the women of
America, I think they are deluded by their own sense of
self-importance,'' Carole Hieatt of San Jose Pro-Life Council said
in a statement.
   In its most recent poll on the subject, the Los Angeles Times
reported on March 19 that 74 percent of the respondents in a
nationwide survey said they believed that abortion was ``morally
wrong,'' but also believed that it was a decision best left to the
individual.
   More than 100 organizations sponsored Sunday's demonstration,
including NOW, Planned Parenthood Association, the California
Abortion Rights Action League and the American Civil Liberties
Union.
