<UNK>Giraffe At Evansville Zoo Dies After Falling on Side</UNK>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evie, an 8-year-old female giraffe, died
Sunday about 11 hours after falling on her side, zoo officials said.
   ``She passed away at 2:30 a.m.,'' said Ted Grannon, operations
curator for the Mesker Park Zoo. The body was taken to Purdue
University in West Lafayette for an autopsy to determine the cause
of death, he said.
   Zoo director Ron Young said Evie fell flat on her side Saturday
about 3:15 p.m., but he was not sure what caused the accident.
   ``She was kind of running around in the sun when all four feet
went our from under her and she landed on her side,'' Young said.
``We don't know if the wind was knocked out of her or whether she
hit her head.''
   Evie had been on her back since the accident, and attempted
about every 30 minutes to get back on her feet, zoo officials said.
   Zoo veterinarians Dr. Craig Butler and Dr. Stan Epperson treated
Evie Saturday night with relaxants, pain relievers and fluids, and
even took X-rays of her neck and her legs but found nothing broken,
Young said.
   Evie, worth $12,000 to $20,000, came to the zoo in 1982 from
Abilene, Texas. Her mate, Gerry, came from the Cheyenne Mountain
Park Zoo in Colorado Springs, Colo., in 1981, Young said.
