<FIRST>u w AM-DebtTalks 5thLd-Writethru a0751 04-02 1103</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Debt Talks, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0751,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third World Debt Relief Plan Gets Major Boost from Industrialized
Nations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf pvs, bgng: ``The $1.3 trillion...'' to make riots
in February sted last month; picks up 12th graf pvs, bgng: ``The endorsement...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration's new plan to provide
debt relief for Third World countries received a major boost on
Sunday when it won endorsement from the world's leading
industrialized countries.
   The endorsement was contained in a joint communique adopted by
the United States, Japan, West Germany, Britain, France, Canada and
Italy. It was issued following almost eight hours of closed-door
discussions conducted by U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady and
his foreign counterparts.
   The U.S. proposal was not mentioned by name in the three-page
joint statement, but the discussion of the changes needed in
current policy showed that the finance ministers were in general
support of the proposals outlined by Brady in a March 10 speech.
   ``Debt strategy should be strengthened by placing greater
emphasis on voluntary debt relief and debt service reduction in
agreement with the commercial banks as a complement to new
lending,'' the finance ministers said.
   Brady said that he was pleased with the endorsement contained in
the joint statement, saying it was unusually detailed on what
approaches now need to be taken and very specific on the need for
prompt action by the international lending agencies.
   ``There was broad support for strengthening the debt strategy
along the lines of the U.S. proposals,'' Brady told reporters after
the meeting had ended.
   Canadian Finance Minister Michael Wilson called the new debt
strategy an important step forward in solving the seven-year-long
debt crisis.
   ``We have a good agreement and we have good support demonstrated
for the proposal,'' he told reporters.
   A senior Treasury official, who briefed reporters, said that
while the communique did not mention specific support to be
provided by other countries, he expected such announcements would
be made later in the week. The administration is looking for
countries running large trade surpluses, such as Japan, to offer to
support the debt reduction effort by providing money for new loans.
   The Brady plan represents a major departure from the debt
approach pursued by the Reagan administration, which had repeatedly
rejected proposals for broad-based debt forgiveness.
   The $1.3 trillion burden of Third World debt has crippled the
economies of developing nations and sparked economic and political
unrest in many emerging democracies in Latin America. Riots left at
least 270 people dead in Venezuela in February after the government
announced a new austerity program to please that country's
creditors.
   The endorsement by America's major allies was the first step in
a sales strategy the administration has put together. Brady now
takes the proposal before meetings on Monday and Tuesday of the
steering committees of the 151-nation International Monetary Fund
and the World Bank.
   The two major lending organizations have key roles to play in
implementation of the new debt relief approach, which the
administration hopes will shave the current debt burden by 20
percent.
   In other comments, the seven industrialized countries reaffirmed
their commitment to stabilize the dollar, saying either a sharp
increase or decline in the greenback's value would be seen as
harmful to worldwide economic growth and would trigger joint
intervention by the nations to buy or sell dollars.
   The countries also told the United States that it needs to do
more to reduce its huge budget deficits and said countries, such as
Japan, which were running large trade surpluses should continue to
promote domestic demand in order to provide markets for foreign
goods.
   U.S. allies have been complaining that America's expected $170
billion federal budget deficit this year threatens worldwide growth
by driving up interest rates, a situation which also adds to the
debt payment burden of poor nations.
   The discussions took place at River Farm, an estate on the
Potomac River which once belonged to George Washington.
   Under the Brady debt plan, commercial banks would be asked to
forgive voluntarily a portion of the loans they have made to poor
nations. In return, the IMF and World Bank would provide assurances
that the remaining debt would be repaid.
   The administration has estimated that over the next three years
the plan could wipe out about $70 billion of the $340 billion in
debt owed by 39 of the most heavily indebted countries.
   The IMF and World Bank would be expected to contribute together
between $20 billion and $25 billion to back the debt reduction
effort with the United States looking to Japan and other countries
running large trade surpluses to assist in the effort by making new
loans.
   U.S. officials have indicated that Mexico, Venezuela and the
Philippines likely would be among the first beneficiaries of any
debt relief strategy.
   But the debtor nations are already complaining that the plan
does not go far enough to provide relief. Some experts have said
that any attack on the problem will have to write off 50 percent or
more of the debt.
   Large U.S. banks, who hold 30 percent of the outstanding Third
World loans, have reacted cautiously to the proposals, fearing that
they could cause a stampede by debtor nations demanding debt
forgiveness.
   Already, officials of Mexico have indicated that they will ask
their bank creditors in upcoming negotiations to either provide new
loans or slash the value of outstanding loans or the interest rates
being paid by half.
   Mexico, which owes $107 billion, is the Third World's second
largest debtor, behind the $110 billion owed by Brazil.
   The Brady plan represents a major departure from the Reagan
administration approach, which emphasized new lending and opposed
any broad-based proposals for debt forgiveness.
   The Reagan approach was crafted by then-Treasury Secretary James
A. Baker III. Baker, who is secretary of state in the Bush
administration, said in a speech last week that the new policy of
debt forgiveness would be negotiated on a country-by-country basis
with the relief going to those debtor nations willing to adopt
necessary economic reforms.
   At the IMF meetings on Sunday, debtor nations issued a statement
attacking the Baker approach to Third World debt while welcoming
the new approach outlined by Brady.
   Jean-Pierre Lemboumba-Lepandou, finance minister of Gabon and
chairman of the committee representing developing countries, said
the Brady plan was ``an important initiative and we are convinced
that it will bear fruit.''
   However, the Gabon finance minister sidestepped questions about
whether the U.S. proposal went far enough to reduce the debt
burden, saying the specifics of the proposal still needed to be
worked out in upcoming meetings.
</TEXT>
