<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-89 2254EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Gallaudet-Zinser 1stLd-Writethru a0657 04-02 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gallaudet-Zinser, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0657,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Year After Gallaudet Protests, Elisabeth Zinser is Heading For
Idaho</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites throughout to CORRECT spelling of Elisabeth, sted Elizabeth,
Zinser.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gallaudet-A Year Later</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elisabeth Ann Zinser, who was forced to
resign last year as the incoming president of the nation's only
university for the deaf, looks back on the incident without
bitterness and says she's ready for a new challenge as president of
the University of Idaho.
   ``I'm a pioneering person,'' she said. ``I feel I have to be
part of something that is poised for development.''
   In March 1988, Ms. Zinser became the focus of a national
controversy when she was selected over two deaf finalists to become
president of Gallaudet University in Washington, D.C.
   For the previous five years, Ms. Zinser had been vice chancellor
for academic affairs at the University of North Carolina at
Greensboro. She stayed at that post when the protest over the
Gallaudet job led her to withdraw before she took office.
   But now she's going to Moscow, Idaho, where she'll start July 1
as the first woman president of the Idaho's 9,500-student flagship
state university.
   She said she hopes to strengthen that school's research efforts
and its ties with the business community, and will work with
Idaho's Indian and Hispanic communities.
   And in an interview last week, she wondered aloud if her
interest in public service was enhanced by her experience with the
deaf students.
   ``I've got an intense desire to make my life count for
something,'' said Ms. Zinser, 49. ``That's why I can't just work
for any institution.''
   Her selection at Gallaudet touched off an immediate protest by
thousands of students, faculty members and their supporters at the
school _ which had never had a deaf president in its 124-year
history.
   The protesters shut down the university, marched and burned Ms.
Zinser in effigy. After three days, she resigned, citing a ``unique
civil-rights movement in history.''
   ``One of my objectives as president of Gallaudet University was
to be succeeded by a deaf person,'' she said with a smile. ``I
accomplished that, perhaps more quickly than I had planned.
   ``I never felt I quit,'' she continued. ``It wasn't a battle
between the students and Elisabeth Zinser, but an effort to reach a
common bond.''
   Ms. Zinser said farewell to the Gallaudet students by flashing
them the ``I love you'' sign. The students later gave her a
personal sign-language nickname: an ``E'' for Elisabeth, held over
the heart.
</TEXT>
